---
import Base from "@/layouts/Base.astro";
import {
  BRAND_NAME,
  SITE_URL,
  PARENT_ORG_URL,
  GITHUB_REPO_URL,
} from "@/lib/config";
import { breadcrumbListSchema } from "@/lib/schema";
import {
  PENALTY_CODE_ORDER,
  PENALTY_META,
  MAX_TOTAL_PENALTY,
} from "@/lib/penalties";

const canonical = `${SITE_URL}/methodology`;
const jsonLd = breadcrumbListSchema([
  { name: "Home", url: SITE_URL },
  { name: "Methodology", url: canonical },
]);
---

<Base
  title={`Methodology — ${BRAND_NAME}`}
  description="How HumanizerBench tests AI humanizers: sample selection, scoring formula, versioning, reproducibility."
  canonical={canonical}
  ogImage={`${SITE_URL}/og/methodology.png`}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article
    class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-16 px-6 text-[var(--color-text-primary)] [&_h1]:text-4xl [&_h1]:font-semibold [&_h1]:tracking-tight [&_h1]:mb-8 [&_h2]:text-2xl [&_h2]:font-semibold [&_h2]:tracking-tight [&_h2]:mt-12 [&_h2]:mb-4 [&_p]:mt-4 [&_p]:leading-relaxed [&_p]:text-[var(--color-text-secondary)] [&_ul]:mt-4 [&_ul]:space-y-2 [&_ul]:pl-6 [&_ul]:list-disc [&_ul]:text-[var(--color-text-secondary)] [&_ol]:mt-4 [&_ol]:space-y-2 [&_ol]:pl-6 [&_ol]:list-decimal [&_ol]:text-[var(--color-text-secondary)] [&_a]:text-[var(--color-accent)] [&_a:hover]:underline [&_code]:font-mono [&_code]:text-[0.9em] [&_code]:px-1 [&_code]:py-0.5 [&_code]:rounded [&_code]:bg-[var(--color-surface)] [&_code]:border [&_code]:border-[var(--color-border)] [&_strong]:font-semibold [&_strong]:text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
  >
    <h1>Methodology</h1>

    <div
      class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]"
    >
      HumanizerBench is operated by WriteHuman (<a href={PARENT_ORG_URL}
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        target="_blank">writehuman.ai</a
      >). We disclose this openly.
      <strong class="text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
        >Methodology and raw data:
        <a href={GITHUB_REPO_URL} rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"
          >GitHub repo</a
        >. Read our <a href="/fairness">fairness policy</a> or <a href="/why"
          >why we built this</a
        >.</strong
      >
    </div>

    <h2>Sample selection</h2>
    <p>
      Each cycle uses a curated set of test prompts spanning eight writing
      categories: <code>academic_essay</code>, <code>application_essay</code>,
      <code>blog_post</code>, <code>marketing_copy</code>, <code
        >business_email</code
      >, <code>lit_review</code>, <code>landing_copy</code>, and <code
        >product_desc</code
      >. Prompts are versioned via <code>prompt_set_version</code> so any
      change to the inputs produces a new, distinguishable cycle. The target
      sample count per humanizer is <strong>72 samples per cycle</strong> (nine
      prompts per category), balanced across the eight categories so no single
      genre dominates the overall score.
    </p>

    <h2>Tested humanizers</h2>
    <p>
      The current cycle tests <strong>8 humanizers</strong>. Slugs and display
      names are listed on the <a href="/leaderboard">leaderboard</a>, and each
      humanizer has a dedicated detail page under <code>/humanizers/[slug]</code
      >. WriteHuman is included on the leaderboard and is held to exactly the
      same methodology, scoring, and penalty rules as every other humanizer.
    </p>

    <h2>Detectors</h2>
    <p>
      We test every humanized output against six independent commercial AI
      detectors:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>GPTZero</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Originality.ai</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Copyleaks</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Winston AI</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Sapling</strong></li>
      <li><strong>ZeroGPT</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Detector results are independent third-party submissions — we do not
      operate, fine-tune, or coordinate with the detectors. For each
      humanizer-output sample we submit the same text to all six detectors and
      record the raw responses, the parsed classification (human / AI), and the
      detector's reported confidence.
    </p>

    <h2>Scoring formula</h2>
    <p>
      The overall score is a weighted blend of five sub-scores, each
      normalized to the 0–1 range:
    </p>
    <pre
      class="mt-4 rounded-md border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-4 font-mono text-sm overflow-x-auto text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"><code>overall = 0.40 * bypass_rate
        + 0.25 * meaning_preservation
        + 0.20 * readability
        + 0.10 * consistency_across_categories
        + 0.05 * speed_score</code></pre>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>bypass_rate</strong> — share of detector tests where the output
        was classified as human (across all six detectors and all samples).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>meaning_preservation</strong> — how well the humanized output
        preserves the original meaning, scored 0–1.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>readability</strong> — how close the humanized output stays to
        the input's reading level.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>consistency_across_categories</strong> — how evenly the
        humanizer performs across the eight writing categories.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>speed_score</strong> — how fast the humanizer responds, per
        request.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Confidence levels</h2>
    <p>Each humanizer carries a confidence label:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>high</strong> — ≥ 60 successful tests in the cycle and low
        variance across categories.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>medium</strong> — 30–59 successful tests, OR high variance
        across categories.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>low</strong> — fewer than 30 successful tests, OR severe
        inconsistency between categories or detectors.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Penalties</h2>
    <p>
      A humanizer's overall score can be reduced by one or more penalties when
      its output exhibits known quality issues. Penalties are deducted from the
      raw overall score; the final score is clamped at 0. Per-humanizer penalty
      deltas are published alongside the cycle data so every deduction is
      auditable.
    </p>
    <p>
      Each penalty has a fixed deduction per occurrence and a cap on its total
      impact, so no single category can dominate the final score. The maximum
      possible total penalty across all codes is <strong
        class="font-mono tabnum">−{MAX_TOTAL_PENALTY.toFixed(1)}</strong
      > (off 100).
    </p>
    <ul>
      {
        PENALTY_CODE_ORDER.map((code) => {
          const m = PENALTY_META[code];
          return (
            <li>
              <strong>{m.label}</strong> (<code>{code}</code>) — {m.description}{" "}
              <span class="font-mono tabnum">
                −{m.per.toFixed(1)} penalty / −{m.cap.toFixed(1)} max.
              </span>
            </li>
          );
        })
      }
    </ul>

    <h2>Versioning</h2>
    <p>Every cycle records five version stamps:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <code>methodology_version</code> — bumped on any change to the formula
        above or to how sub-scores are computed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>scoring_version</code> — bumped alongside
        <code>methodology_version</code>; identifies the exact scoring script
        revision used.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>prompt_set_version</code> — bumped whenever any input prompt is
        added, removed, or edited.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>detector_config_version</code> — bumped when a detector's
        endpoint, parser, or threshold configuration changes.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>humanizer_config_version</code> — bumped when a humanizer's
        endpoint, parameters, or pricing tier we tested against changes.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Bump rules: any change to the formula → both <code
        >methodology_version</code
      > and <code>scoring_version</code>. Prompt changes → <code
        >prompt_set_version</code
      >. Detector config changes → <code>detector_config_version</code>.
    </p>

    <h2>Reproducibility</h2>
    <p>
      Everything you need to reproduce a cycle is public: <a
        href={GITHUB_REPO_URL}
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        target="_blank">{GITHUB_REPO_URL}</a
      >. Every input, every humanized output, every detector response, every
      scoring script — public.
    </p>

    <h2>Methodology integrity</h2>
    <p>
      WriteHuman does not manually adjust rankings. Rankings are generated from
      the published benchmark data using the scoring formula on this page. The
      scoring script is in our public repository: <a
        href={GITHUB_REPO_URL}
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        target="_blank">{GITHUB_REPO_URL}</a
      >.
    </p>

    <h2>How to contribute or dispute</h2>
    <p>
      If you've found an error, want to dispute a score, request a retest, or
      submit API access so we can test your humanizer programmatically, see
      <a href="/fairness">our fairness &amp; corrections policy</a> for the
      contact addresses and the response-time commitment.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
